<outline text="JOE 1.8.8"/>
<outline text="Installation"/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="---------------------------------"/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="Contents"/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="I. All Platforms"/>
<outline text="II. Windows"/>
<outline text="III. Unix/Linux/Solaris"/>
<outline text="IV. &lt;forthcoming&gt; Macintosh OS X"/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="---------------------------------"/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="I. All Platforms"/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="1) When you first run JOE you should examine, and customize as desired, JOE's application preferences.">
	<outline text="Give the Edit:Application Preferences menu command. "/>
	<outline text="The Application Preferences dialog appears. "/>
	<outline text="Go through the preference panels, and set the items as desired."/>
</outline>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="---------------------------------"/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="II. Windows "/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="0) Operating System Requirements">
	<outline text="Windows 95 or later"/>
	<outline text="Windows NT 4 or later"/>
</outline>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="1) Ensure that your system has an appropriate Java 2 Runtime Environment (JRE) installed. ">
	<outline text="That means at least version 1.3. The latest 1.4 beta should also work, although we have not tested it."/>
	<outline text="To determine what JRE, if any, is installed on your system:">
		<outline text="Give the Start:Settings:Control Panel menu command. "/>
		<outline text="Run the Add/Remove Programs applet. "/>
		<outline text="Look for entries in the list of installed software with Java in their names, such as Java 2 Runtime or Java 2 SDK."/>
	</outline>
	<outline text="You can download JREs and Java 2 SDKs (which include JREs)as follows: ">
		<outline text="JRE 1.3.1_02:">
			<outline text="http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.3/jre/download-windows.html"/>
		</outline>
		<outline text="Java 2 SDK 1.3.1_02:">
			<outline text="http://java.sun.com/j2se/1.3/download-windows.html"/>
		</outline>
	</outline>
</outline>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="2) If you discover in step 1) that your system has more than one JRE, edit the Outliner directory's run.bat file so that it invokes the particular java.exe runtime you want JOE to run under.">
	<outline text="Determine the pathname for the java runtime .exe file you want to run.">
		<outline text="One way to do this: give the following command from the root directory of the drive you are examining in an MS-DOS command line window:">
			<outline text="dir java.exe /s"/>
		</outline>
	</outline>
	<outline text="There's a line near the end of run.bat that invokes the Java runtime. It looks like this:">
		<outline text="java -cp %CP% -Xincgc com.organic.maynard.outliner.Outliner en"/>
	</outline>
	<outline text="Edit that line so that it uses the pathname determined above.">
		<outline text="Example:">
			<outline text="C:\Program Files\JavaSoft\JRE\1.3.1_02\bin\java -cp %CP% -Xincgc com.organic.maynard.outliner.Outliner en"/>
		</outline>
	</outline>
</outline>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="3) If you haven't already, download and decompress JOE">
	<outline text="You can obtain the download here:">
		<outline text="http://JavaOutlineEditor.org/downloads/"/>
	</outline>
	<outline text="The decompressed package lives in a directory named Outliner"/>
</outline>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="4) Run the program windows_setup.exe, located in JOE's Outliner directory. "/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="5) Reboot your system."/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="6) Run JOE.">
	<outline text="There's a JOE shortcut file in the Outliner directory. It's the file with the black/purple/yellow/white JOE icon. Double-click it to run JOE. ">
		<outline text="Actually, its complete name is JOE.pif, but most Windows systems will show just the JOE part of its name."/>
	</outline>
	<outline text="You can copy and paste the JOE shortcut file that's in the Outliner Directory to the Windows desktop, the Program menu, the top of the Start menu, andor the Taskbar's QuickLaunch toolbar. It will work from any of those locations, and from any location on any of your drives."/>
	<outline text=""/>
</outline>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="7) Option: Use the sendto.bat file to set up Windows &quot;sendto&quot;.">
	<outline text="In sendto.bat, change the path for cd to the directory you installed JOE into."/>
</outline>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="8) Note: If you move, rename, or copy the Outliner directory containing JOE, just re-run steps 4) and 5) to get JOE working correctly from the new/renamed location."/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="---------------------------------"/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="III. UNIX/Linux/Solaris:"/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="1) Edit run_joe.sh so that INSTALL_DIR points to the directory you installed JOE into.">
	<outline text="Make sure to make it executable and put it somewhere in your PATH. "/>
	<outline text=""/>
	<outline text="Note: something like this"/>
	<outline text=""/>
	<outline text="   run_joe ../../file.opml "/>
	<outline text=""/>
	<outline text="won't work. Because it needs to change in to the JOE directory to run it, the script "/>
	<outline text="cuts off any path info, and then adds on the current directory, so it always passes $CWD/filename.opml to JOE. "/>
</outline>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="---------------------------------"/>
<outline text=""/>
<outline text="IV. &lt;forthcoming&gt; Macintosh OS X"/>
